form.name: Scouse
associations: There's varying levels of strength to the accent, from the rounded out slightly posh south end accent of Mossley Hill and the like, to the much imitated wacker accent. Scouse has it's own rhyming slang, with some of its origins being an ancient kind of pop culture. People will be heard saying " wanna gerra jobe" when asking for a taxi (Joe Baksi, 1940's boxer). A fine example of the early sort of scouse can be found in Fritz Spiegl's Lern Yerself Scouse books. A favourite of mine was "He Lispeth Sailor" being translated as Richard Burton's Wife.
